# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1932-washington-senators-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The **1901 major league baseball season** was contested from April 18 through October 6, 1901.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural major league season for the American League (AL) (having previously been the minor league Western League), with the Chicago White Stockings winning the AL pennant.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Pittsburgh Pirates won the NL pennant.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of the modern era.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the only season in which the Milwaukee Brewers played, as the team would relocate to St.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, Missouri for the following season as the St.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns (before that team relocated to Baltimore, Maryland as the modern Baltimore Orioles in 1954, where they remain to this day.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles of this season would fold following the 1902 season).
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The 1901 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 18 with a game between the Brooklyn Superbas and the Philadelphia Phillies, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 24, with a game between the Chicago White Stockings and the Cleveland Bluebirds.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the season on September 28, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 6.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] On February 27, 1901, the National League Rules Committee announced several rule changes, effective immediately.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games (8 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds would play their final game at League Park, on October 6 during a doubleheader against the St.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, moving into the Palace of the Fans for the start of the 1902 season.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1901-washington-senators-season] The 1901 Washington Senators won 61 games, lost 72, and finished in sixth place in the American League in its first year as a major league team.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1901-washington-senators-season] They were managed by Jim Manning and played home games at the American League Park I.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1902-washington-senators-season] The **1902 Washington Senators** won 61 games, lost 75, and finished in sixth place in the American League.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1902-washington-senators-season] They were managed by Tom Loftus and played home games at the American League Park I.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1903-washington-senators-season] The **1903 Washington Senators** won 43 games, lost 94, and finished in eighth place in the American League.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1903-washington-senators-season] Washington had finished in sixth place in each of the previous two seasons (the first two seasons of the American League's existence).
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1903-washington-senators-season] However, they fell to eighth and last in 1903.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1903-washington-senators-season] Their only star player, Big Ed Delahanty, got drunk and fell off a bridge into Niagara Falls midway through the season.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1903-washington-senators-season] The Senators' pitching had always been bad, and indeed, they would allow the most runs in the AL, but without Delahanty the offense sputtered to a halt.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1903-washington-senators-season] Their collective batting average was .231, bad even for the dead-ball era, and no one drove in more than 49 runs.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1904-washington-senators-season] The **1904 Washington Senators** won 38 games, lost 113, and finished in eighth place in the American League.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1904-washington-senators-season] They were managed by Malachi Kittridge and Patsy Donovan and played home games at National Park.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1904-washington-senators-season] Their winning percentage of .252 is fourth worst for any MLB team since 1900.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1905-washington-senators-season] The **1905 Washington Senators** won 64 games, lost 87, and finished in seventh place in the American League.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1905-washington-senators-season] They were managed by Jake Stahl and played home games at National Park.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1906-washington-senators-season] The **1906 Washington Senators** won 55 games, lost 95, and finished in seventh place in the American League.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1906-washington-senators-season] Shortstop Joe Cassidy died in March 1906 due to complications from typhoid and malaria.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1906-washington-senators-season] The Senators opened their 1906 season against the Philadelphia Athletics at Columbia Park in Philadelphia.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1932-washington-senators-season] The **1932 Washington Senators** won 93 games, lost 61, and finished in third place in the American League.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1932-washington-senators-season] They were managed by Walter Johnson and played home games at Griffith Stadium.
[src:1932-washington-senators-season/1932-washington-senators-season] The 1932 Washington Senators were the last team in the 20th century to have 100 triples in one season.
